The paper deals with numerical algorithms for linear algebra and optimization, which are relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. The use of preconditioners and randomized procedures suggests a focus on numerical analysis and scientific computing, which is reflected in the cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) category. The mention of convex optimization and linear programming suggests a connection to machine learning and optimization, which are covered by the cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) categories. The use of linear regression and projection also suggests a connection to information theory and signal processing, which are covered by the cs.IT (Information Theory) category. Finally, the mention of image processing and computer vision suggests a connection to computer vision and graphics, which are covered by the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) category.
